metadata.name: Holy Mountain #85
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

metadata.name: Provence #431
metadata.description:
The south of France namely the Provence has a cultural history of being an inspiration for impressionists and post-impressionists in the past.
For me personally the Provence is the place i was spending long, peaceful holidays as a child within beautiful nature.
This work does not so much aim for being realistic, rather than give an impression or feeling for this wonderful landscape. 
There are just a few different elements and concepts and yet there is variety of fascinating results.
I really hope you will enjoy your minting.

Notes:
STARTUP AND RENDERING MAY TAKE SOME TIME. (Up to 1min)
Code was written in typescript.
The only used libraries were chroma.js and simplex-noise

metadata.name: 4rtiu5 #47
metadata.description:
Wiki

A circle is a shape consisting of all points in a plane that are at a given distance from a given point, the centre. Equivalently, it is the curve traced out by a point that moves in a plane so that its distance from a given point is constant. The distance between any point of the circle and the centre is called the radius.

Name

So, I kinda have a thing with language so I tried to find a funny mix of "art" or "genart" and "circle" or "radius".
I ended up using "radius", scrambled it a bit which became "arduis" and replace "ard" with "art". 
The 4 and the S mean like "4 us", hence "4rtiu5" :-)

Project

There aren't much properties that are set, except for "dashed lines" and "blurred gutters". I had a lot of fun making this and was amazed by some really great outputs myself, I hope you guys like it too! :-)
Cheers üçª

metadata.name: The Hypothetical Motherboards V2.0 #108
metadata.description:
The V2.0 fix a bug in the V1.0.
Remaining V1.0 tokes have been burned, and I will airdrop V2.0 token to the V1.0 owners.

An algorithm that combine 19 differents tiles to a unique piece that may look like a motherboard.

There are 19 different tiles design, 6 styles, 32 Color Schemes and 4 specials features.

Pieces are generated by spreading the core tiles on the canvas plus an amount of processor is added. Finally, a finishing pass is made by smartly adding connector tiles where they are needed. Connector tiles have either 1,2,3 or 4 sides to connect with.

# GENERATIVE FEATURES

## Processor count
The more processor, the rarest
- 4 processors (‚âÉ35% of chance)
- 5 processors (‚âÉ25% of chance)
- 6 processors (‚âÉ15% of chance)
- 8 processors (‚âÉ10% of chance)
- 16 processors (‚âÉ5% of chance)

## Color scheme
There are 32 different color schemes and 6 different filling style, Gradient, Textured, Stripes, Moir√©, Flat and Op Art.
- randomly picked, all themes have the same probability of being picked

## Filling style
Filling are distributed as follow :
- 14 Gradient (‚âÉ45% of total)
- 7 Texture (‚âÉ21% of total)
- 6 Flat (‚âÉ18% of total)
- 3 Moir√© (‚âÉ10% of total)
- 1 Stripes (‚âÉ3% of total)
- 1 Op Art (‚âÉ3% of total)

## Special Feature
3 themes have 2 special features, 18 themes have 1 special feature and 11 themes have 0 special features.

Features are distributed as follow :
- 18 color schemes are Animated (‚âÉ56% of total)
- 7 color schemes have no feature (‚âÉ21% of total)
- 4 color schemes have Grainy textures (‚âÉ12% of total)
- 2 color schemes are Alien (‚âÉ6% of total)
- 2 color schemes are Rusted (‚âÉ6% of total)
- 1 color schemes have Stars (‚âÉ3% of total)
- 1 color schemes have Heart (‚âÉ3% of total)

## Tiles density
Tiles density is calculated regarding the amount of total tiles added and will be dependent of the tiles density of the core, processor and connector and will be either "Crowded", "Filed", "Mostly Filed", "Average", "Sparse", "Very Sparse" or "Scattered"

metadata.name: KINJO! #28
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)
